etymologies: late 15th century; earliest use found in Catholicon Anglicum: an English-Latin wordbook. Origin unknown

definitions: A gill of a fish. Usually in plural.

notes.text: Sc. National Dict. (at cited word) records the word as still in use in Ayrshire in 1954, but marks it as obsolescent.

etymologies: early 19th century; earliest use found in John Rennie (1761–1821), engineer. From ginnle

definitions: To tickle (a fish, a fish's gills or belly); to catch (fish, especially trout) by tickling the gills or belly. Also without object: to hunt (for fish) in this way with the hands, or with a small loop attached to a stick.
